StringWithMarkup.String: Methyl phenylacetate's production and use as a synthetic food flavoring agent may result in its release to the environment through various waste streams. Its use in the manufacture of synthetic perfumes may result in its direct release to the environment. Methyl phenylacetate is a component of various plant species and some Mycobacterium species. If released to air, a vapor pressure of 0.13 mm Hg at 20 °C indicates methyl phenylacetate will exist solely as a vapor in the atmosphere. Vapor-phase methyl phenylacetate will be degraded in the atmosphere by reaction with photochemically-produced hydroxyl radicals; the half-life for this reaction in air is estimated to be 8.6 days. Methyl phenylacetate does not absorb UV light at wavelengths >290 nm and, therefore, is not expected to be susceptible to direct photolysis by sunlight. If released to soil, methyl phenylacetate is expected to have high mobility based upon an estimated Koc of 74. Volatilization from moist soil surfaces may be an important fate process based upon an estimated Henry's Law constant of 1.4X10-5 atm-cu m/mole. Methyl phenylacetate has a vapor pressure of 0.13 mm Hg and exists as a liquid under environmental conditions; therefore, methyl phenylacetate may volatilize from dry soil. Utilizing the Closed Bottle test, 75% degradation was reached in 28 days indicating that biodegradation is an important environmental fate process in soil and water. If released into water, methyl phenylacetate is not expected to adsorb to suspended solids and sediment based upon the estimated Koc. Volatilization from water surfaces may be an important fate process based upon this compound's estimated Henry's Law constant. Estimated volatilization half-lives for a model river and model lake are 2 and 28 days, respectively. An estimated BCF of 7.5 suggests the potential for bioconcentration in aquatic organisms is low. Methyl phenylacetate may undergo slow hydrolysis in alkaline soils and waters. Occupational exposure to methyl phenylacetate may occur through inhalation and dermal contact with this compound at workplaces where methyl phenylacetate is produced or used. Limited monitoring data and use data indicate that the general population may be exposed to methyl phenylacetate via ingestion of food, smoking cigarettes and inhalation and dermal contact with consumer products containing methyl phenylacetate. Section.Description: Sorption to soils and sediments is an important factor on the transport and fate of organic contaminants in the environment.  The soil/water adsorption coefficient, also known as solid-water distribution coefficient (Kd), measures the amount of chemical substance adsorbed onto soil per amount of water.  Since adsorption occurs predominantly by partition into the soil organic matter, it is more useful to normalize the Kd value to the organic carbon content of a soil and express the distribution coefficient in Koc (organic carbon normalized distribution coefficient).  The greater the Kd (or Koc) value, the less likely a chemical will leach or contribute to runoff.  A very high value means it is strongly adsorbed onto soil and organic matter and does not move throughout the soil.

Our mission is to lead the development of a balanced and effective international Intellectual Property (IP) system that enables innovation and creativity for the benefit of all. We help governments, businesses and society realize the benefits of Intellectual Property and are notably a world reference source for IP information.
LinkOut is a service that allows one to link directly from NCBI databases to a wide range of information and services beyond NCBI systems.
